    "explanation": "• Prothrombin time (PT) is an indicator of extrinsic and common pathway <br>of coagulation. <br>• Activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT) is a measure of intrinsic <br>and common pathway. <br>• PT and APTT—both are prolonged when there is defect in common <br>pathway, liver dysfunction, DIC. <br>• Diagnostic approach to bleeding disorders by laboratory investigation— <br>Increased bleeding time <br>Increased clotting time <br>a. Platelet count decreased—<br>ITP, purpura secondary to <br>asplenia, leukemia, drugs <br> <br>b. Platelet count normal—<br>anaphylactoid purpura <br>a. Only PT prolonged—factor VII deficiency <br><br> b. Only APTT prolonged—deficiency of <br>factors VIII, IX, XI, XII, and Von Willebrand’s <br>disease <br> c. Both PT and APTT <br>prolonged—vitamin K deficiency, severe liver <br>disease, deficiency of factors V and X",
    "year": "2005",
