    "question": "Which one of the following is not a feature of Sturge-Weber syndrome  (encephalotrigeminal syndrome)?",
    "options": {
      "a": "\"Railroad track\" calcification",
      "b": "Focal convulsion",
      "c": "Hemiatrophy of brain",
      "d": "Empty sella"
    },
    "answer": "d",
    "explanation": "Sturge-Weber syndrome—when a port wine stain is <br>localized to trigeminal area of face, especially around the eyelids, the <br>diagnosis of Sturge-Weber syndrome (ipsilateral glaucoma, leptomeningeal <br>venous angioma, mental retardation, seizures, hemiparesis contralateral to <br>facial lesion, intracranial calcification) must be considered. <br>• Facial nevus—present at birth, unilateral and always involves upper <br>face and eyelids. <br>• Seizure—focal tonic-clonic, contralateral to facial nevus, mostly during <br>1st year of life (Jacksonian epilepsy). <br>• Skull radiograph—intracranial calcification (serpentine or railroad track <br>appearance) in occipitoparietal region. <br>• MRI—most sensitive for demonstrating cerebral lesions.",
    "year": "2005",
