    "question": "The most common histological type seen in bronchogenic carcinoma is",
    "options": {
      "a": "Small cell carcinoma",
      "b": "Large cell carcinoma",
      "c": "Squamous cell carcinoma",
      "d": "Adenocarcinoma"
    },
    "answer": "d",
    "explanation": "• Adenocarcinoma- most common histological type, common histological <br>type in young patients and in females, metastases to opposite lung, <br>peripheral distribution. <br>• Squamous cell carcinoma- most common histological type in India, <br>cavitate, central distribution (pancoast tumor is peripheral tumor of <br>squamous variety), hypercalcemia due to PTH, best prognosis. <br>• Small cell lung cancers- known as oat cell cancers because of the <br>packed nature of small dense cells. They are a type of neuroendocrine <br>tumour, having early metastasis. The pattern of disease, the prognosis <br>and the results of treatment for small cell (also known as oat cell) <br>carcinoma differ from all other types sufficiently for these to be <br>managed differently on the basis of the histological classification. <br>• C/F- Clinical features depend on: the site of the lesion, invasion of <br>neighbouring structures, extent of metastases. Hemoptysis is present <br>in<50%, cough is most common non specific complain. Cigarette <br>smoking is major risk factor for lung carcinoma and accounts for 85-<br>95% of all cases. To a lesser extent, atmospheric pollution and certain <br>occupations (mining of radioactive ore and chromium) contribute.",
    "year": "2005",
    "paper": "1",
