    "explanation": "Pathogenesis of asthma: <br>Extrinsic (atopic, allergic) asthma, <br>immune type 1 hypersensitivity <br>reaction <br>Intrinsic asthma, <br>abnormal autonomic <br>regulation of airways <br>should be in one line <br>Mixed, <br>exercise <br>induced, or <br>aspirin <br>induced <br>• Family history preceding allergic <br>disease such as rhinitis, urticaria, or <br>infantile eczema <br>• No family history <br> <br>• Starts in childhood <br>• Starts in adult life <br> <br>• Predisposition to form IgE <br>antibodies [activated TH2 cells are <br>increased numbers in asthma and <br>produce IL4 that initiate humoral <br>(IgE) immune response]. <br>• IgE antibodies may be <br>formed but no particular <br>predisposition <br> <br>• Allergens recognized—pollen, <br>dandruff, house dust, mite <br>• No recognizable <br>allergens <br> <br>• Attacks often diminished in later <br>years <br>• Attacks increase in <br>severity <br> <br>• Chronic bronchitis seldom develops <br>• Associated with nasal <br>polyp and chronic <br>bronchitis <br> <br>• Emphysema unusual <br>• Emphysema <br>commonly develops <br> <br>• No drug sensitivity <br>• Drug sensitivity may <br>develop (aspirin, <br>penicillin) <br> <br>Inhalation of allergen leads to biphasic response: | Early reaction | Late <br>phase | | :--- | :--- | | • Within 10 minutes of exposure to allergens. | • <br>Occurs in about two-thirds of patients. | | • Release of histamine, leukotriene <br>C4, D4, and E4, prostaglandins, platelet-activating factor, and bradykinin from <br>mast cells. | • It develops 3–4 hours later with peak at 8–12 hours. | | • This <br>phase is inhibited by β2-agonist drugs and mast cell-stabilizing agents <br>(cromolyn or nedocromil). | • Release of mast cell mediators. <br> • Not <br>prevented by premedication with β2-agonist drugs <br> • Inhibited by <br>premedication with steroids and cromolyn or nedocromil |",
    "year": "2005",
    "paper": "1",
    "tags": [
      "Pediatrics"
    ]
