    "explanation": "Organisms causing <br>endocarditis: <br>1. Native-valve endocarditis: a. Community acquired—Staphylococcus <br>aureus (most common), streptococci b. Nosocomial—S. aureus (most <br>common), enterococci <br>2. Prosthetic valve endocarditis at indicated time of onset (months) after <br>valve surgery: a. <2 months—coagulase-negative staphylococci (most <br>common), S. aureus b. 2–12 months—coagulase-negative <br>Staphylococcus (most common), S.aureus, and enterococci c. >12 <br>months—streptococci (most common), S. aureus <br>3. Endocarditis in injection drug users: a. Right sided—S. aureus b. Left <br>sided—enterococci, S. aureus c. Total—S. aureus.",
