    "explanation": "Tricuspid regurgitation • Specific features: (i) <br>Prominent \"V\" wave in jugular venous pressure (JVP), (ii) systolic pulsation of <br>liver, (iii) systolic murmur at left lower sternal border increasing intensity with <br>inspiration, (iv) right ventricular 3rd sound or short tricuspid delayed diastolic <br>murmur increasing during inspiration may be audible in marked TR. • As a rule, <br>almost all patients with TR also have features of pulmonary artery <br>hypertension. • ECG shows changes characteristic of enlargement of right <br>ventricle. [In aortic regurgitation, the ECG shows some increase in left <br>ventricular voltages with deep \"S\" wave in V1 and tall \"R\" wave in V6. There is <br>also deep \"Q\" wave in left chest leads accompanied by tall \"T\" wave. The <br>pattern of deep \"Q\" wave and tall \"T\" wave has been called the \"diastolic <br>overloading pattern\" of left ventricle].",
    "year": "2005",
