    "id": "UPSC_2005_P2_Q104",
    "num": "104",
    "question": "The following are indications for lower segment cesarean section  except",
    "options": {
      "a": "Fetal distress in first stage of labor",
      "b": "Severe degree of contracted pelvis",
      "c": "Cancer cervix diagnosed at 38 weeks of pregnancy",
      "d": "Previous two cesarean sections"
    },
    "answer": "c",
    "explanation": "Indications of present day classical cesarean section <br>1. Lower segment cannot be easily approached due to dense adhesions, <br>presence of fibroids, or marked contraction of the pelvis in <br>kyphoscoliotic pelvis. <br>2. The lower uterine segment is highly vascular due to the underlying <br>placenta previa. <br>3. The lower segment is infiltrated with advanced cancer of the cervix. <br>After delivery of the baby, a Wertheim's operation may be performed. <br>4. In occasional cases of obstructed labor due to transverse lie and an <br>impacted shoulder presentation. <br>5. Threatened rupture or dehiscence or previous classical scar. <br>6. Rare cases of conjoined twins. Reference: Dutta, Textbook of Obstetrics, <br>7th Ed. Pg. 590.",
    "year": "2005",
    "paper": "2",
